WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.866 --> 00:00:02.600
MATT MCNEILL: Hi everyone.

00:00:02.600 --> 00:00:03.080
I'm Matt.

00:00:03.080 --> 00:00:04.260
This is Tom.

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:09.050
Welcome to the session, Here
Be BigQuery at I/O. Just

00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:12.070
before I start, I've got a bit
of a confession to make.

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:14.650
I developed a bit of
an addiction over

00:00:14.650 --> 00:00:16.360
the last six months.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:21.600
It started back in November, and
someone internally sent me

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:25.850
an email with an invitation
to "join the resistance."

00:00:25.850 --> 00:00:27.515
For anyone who's played Ingress,
you all know what

00:00:27.515 --> 00:00:28.200
that means.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:31.180
I've gone through about
two pairs of shoes.

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:33.410
I've walked more miles in the
last six months than I think

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:35.380
I've walked in the
last six years.

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:38.660
It's been a really interesting
experience, because it's

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:42.750
probably been one of the most
engaging, social, fun sort of

00:00:42.750 --> 00:00:45.430
games I've played in years.

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:49.950
And I've been working a lot over
the last few months, few

00:00:49.950 --> 00:00:53.110
years, in social gaming,
particularly working with some

00:00:53.110 --> 00:00:56.000
big gaming customers
in Europe, Gamesys

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.190
being one of them.

00:00:57.190 --> 00:01:01.310
And it really got me thinking,
how do you create that sort of

00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:04.150
level of engagement in a game?

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:05.820
You look at a game
like Ingress--

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:09.380
how do you get that level
of addiction in a game?

00:01:09.380 --> 00:01:13.250
So when I started looking at
this, you see these statistics

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:15.410
that actually have been around
for a couple of years.

00:01:15.410 --> 00:01:18.950
But so many games that
developers are building, they

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:22.200
get installed once, and then
they're never played again.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:25.070
Something like 25%.

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:28.590
And if you're writing a game,
the finances associated with

00:01:28.590 --> 00:01:30.630
these-- the real business
of a game--

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:31.940
is difficult.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:36.030
An average game life cycle can
range between weeks and

00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:38.640
months, but let's say
five or six weeks.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:40.970
When you're planning your
business, that's when you're

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:42.870
going to try to make
the money.

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:45.950
But if you can crack this
engagement problem, you can

00:01:45.950 --> 00:01:49.450
start pushing out beyond that,
and everything that comes

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:51.490
after that is profit.

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:53.190
And that's important when you're
really in the business

00:01:53.190 --> 00:01:55.090
of casual gaming.

00:01:55.090 --> 00:01:58.730
So I started thinking about what
are some of the drivers

00:01:58.730 --> 00:01:59.450
around this.

00:01:59.450 --> 00:02:01.820
And one of the big trends
that I've seen come up--

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:04.750
and this is some basic research
I did on Google

00:02:04.750 --> 00:02:08.180
Trends-- was there's a big trend
coming up around social

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:11.160
gaming and the connected game.

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:14.170
Of course, if you don't have
a connected game, it's very

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:17.000
difficult to actually
make it social.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.930
A game back end enables that
social dimension to a game.

00:02:20.930 --> 00:02:22.800
Ingress is a good example,
of course, in

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:23.830
quite an extreme way.

00:02:23.830 --> 00:02:25.590
Though there's some other
drivers that came

00:02:25.590 --> 00:02:27.630
out as well for that.

00:02:27.630 --> 00:02:30.450
Second was-- this surprised me,
actually-- but a lot of

00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:33.220
people are starting to create
connected games to push some

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:37.240
of their game logic out of the
client for piracy issues.

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:41.530
So there's a great story in
the press a few weeks ago,

00:02:41.530 --> 00:02:45.050
where someone had built
a game simulation--

00:02:45.050 --> 00:02:48.530
a simulation game of
a game company.

00:02:48.530 --> 00:02:50.970
And what they were able to do
is detect whether the client

00:02:50.970 --> 00:02:52.860
had been pirated or not.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:55.770
And they played a bit of a
joke, and made sure that

00:02:55.770 --> 00:02:59.060
anyone who'd pirated the game,
their company went bust.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.940
The virtual company went bust
because of pirates.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:05.110
And there were all these forums
online where people

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:06.630
were, oh my god, this
game's awful!

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:09.120
I keep getting done
by pirates!

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:10.380
Yes.

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:11.420
It was great.

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:12.990
And this is the sort
of fun that people

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:14.270
are starting to have.

00:03:14.270 --> 00:03:16.800
But I think probably one of
the most important areas,

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.565
actually, comes out
of measurement.

00:03:18.565 --> 00:03:21.390
If you've got a connected game,
you can start measuring

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:25.220
in a way that really has not
been possible before.

00:03:25.220 --> 00:03:28.690
And I think one of the reasons
I was really keen on doing

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:32.130
this session is I think some of
the work that Tom's done in

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:35.140
Gamesys is some of the most
advanced work I've seen in

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:40.160
really developing this idea of
a science of engagement,

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:43.550
retention, and keeping those
users playing the game.

00:03:43.550 --> 00:03:46.115
So I'm going to hand over at
this point, Tom Newton,

00:03:46.115 --> 00:03:48.282
Director of Social
Gaming, Gamesys.

