00:11:52.070 --> 00:11:53.590
So it's very, very important
that if we want to keep them

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:56.370
engaged, we need to be
constantly releasing new and

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:57.880
better content for this game.

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:09.840
Great.

00:12:09.840 --> 00:12:11.440
So, all right.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:12.850
So we've sort of painted a
little bit of a picture.

00:12:12.850 --> 00:12:14.790
We've got a lot of players,
they're running around,

00:12:14.790 --> 00:12:16.060
they're doing all these
different activities.

00:12:16.060 --> 00:12:19.530
They can visit friends, they can
send gifts, they can farm

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:21.660
on their homesteads, they
can craft items,

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:24.060
they can collect items.

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:25.210
So what does this mean?

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:29.520
Well, what it means is that we
generate a ton of events.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:34.410
There's a lot of raw data,
and that raw data--

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:36.800
I'd say five or six years ago,
you probably wouldn't have

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:40.940
recorded every single little
step that a player made and

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:42.000
all of the different
properties that

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:43.870
go along with that.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:46.470
But today, it's pretty much
a necessity if you want to

00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:48.470
operate one of these games,
and you want to operate it

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:52.770
well and optimize it and run
it as a solid business.

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:53.930
But that means you're
going to generate a

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:55.600
huge amount of data.

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:57.610
And just to give you an idea of
the sorts of levels of data

00:12:57.610 --> 00:12:59.800
that we see-- and to be honest,
there are plenty of

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.090
other companies that are
probably generating

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:02.640
even more than this.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:05.650
"Here Be Monsters" right now has
got about 10,000 people in

00:13:05.650 --> 00:13:08.180
a limited beta on Facebook.

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:11.210
And those 10,000 players are
generating about a million

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:14.010
sessions a month, and
about 200 million

00:13:14.010 --> 00:13:15.130
unique events a month.

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:19.670
So 200 million actions taken
by 10,000 daily actives.

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:22.300
We've got other games currently
that are running.

00:13:22.300 --> 00:13:25.400
Game 2 there, launched about
three months ago, has already

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:27.620
got 150,000 people playing
it every day.

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:33.050
They're generating about
500 million events

00:13:33.050 --> 00:13:34.380
every single month.

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:36.670
And then one of our larger games
is generating in the

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:38.196
billions of events
every month.

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.670
All of this data goes
into BigQuery.

00:13:43.670 --> 00:13:46.450
And the reason why we really
like BigQuery at Gamesys is

00:13:46.450 --> 00:13:50.810
that it's managed, so there's
almost nothing you need to do

00:13:50.810 --> 00:13:53.790
to get set up.

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:55.230
It scales.

00:13:55.230 --> 00:13:56.690
I'm going to say this
a lot today.

00:13:56.690 --> 00:14:00.640
We really cannot integrate with
a service where we think

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:02.880
that it can't scale, and
BigQuery definitely has a lot

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.380
of power and can do the sorts
of things that we

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:06.180
want to do with it.

00:14:06.180 --> 00:14:09.120
And then also the fact that
you're just writing SQL.

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:11.660
Anybody can write a BigQuery,
and that's pretty awesome,

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:14.870
because our analysts don't like
training days and this

00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:16.120
sort of thing.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:20.060
Because they already know SQL,
and they know it really well,

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:22.360
the transition is extremely easy
for them to go and start

00:14:22.360 --> 00:14:24.185
writing big, powerful queries.

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:31.020
So to give you an idea of what
happens within our platform,

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:32.510
every day, we've got all these
players coming in, they're

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:35.460
playing the game, doing all
these different things, having

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:36.630
a lot of fun.

00:14:36.630 --> 00:14:42.000
And at night, we aggregate all
of that events data into a

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.480
couple of aggregated tables
just for convenience.

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:49.920
And then we also upload all of
the raw events into a table

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:51.170
within BigQuery.

00:14:55.420 --> 00:14:58.950
So these aggregations, these
aggregated tables, they're

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:01.780
there for convenience, but they
help us drive, really,

00:15:01.780 --> 00:15:03.175
just high level KPI reporting.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.490
Just to give you an idea of a
couple of the tables that we

00:15:09.490 --> 00:15:12.290
use fairly consistently across
all of our games-- and you may

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:14.470
want to define different ones
depending on the style of game

00:15:14.470 --> 00:15:14.970
or application--

00:15:14.970 --> 00:15:19.580
I mean, I think this applies to
really any digital product.

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:20.770
The first is profiles.

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:23.280
So profiles, when they're
aggregated at night, you get a

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:25.610
picture of what that user's
state looked like at the end

00:15:25.610 --> 00:15:28.170
of the day, and that's
fairly important.

00:15:28.170 --> 00:15:30.060
Sessions are fairly
self-explanatory.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:34.690
They're essentially aggregated
groups of events that match a

00:15:34.690 --> 00:15:37.510
user's play periods.

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:39.170
And then we have transactions.

00:15:39.170 --> 00:15:41.650
So transactions, obviously,
are really important.

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:42.900
They drive the entire
business.

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:46.900
We want to know when did someone
make a purchase, very,

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:50.290
very specifically, so that we
can go and really dig into,

00:15:50.290 --> 00:15:52.860
what motivated them to
make that purchase?

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:55.860
What did they do once they
bought that virtual currency

00:15:55.860 --> 00:15:57.740
or virtual good?

00:15:57.740 --> 00:15:59.390
How did they spend that
within the game?

00:15:59.390 --> 00:16:01.670
What sort of activities did they
engage with afterwards?

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:05.630
It's really, really important
that we dig in and understand

00:16:05.630 --> 00:16:09.180
the purchasing behavior and the
behavior of our players,

00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:10.660
especially around the
time of purchase.

00:16:13.370 --> 00:16:15.420
So hopefully, I've been able
to paint a little bit of a

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:19.600
picture about what the game
is, what kind of data it

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:24.510
generates, the volumes of data
that it generates, and that we

00:16:24.510 --> 00:16:28.810
effectively every night update
a number of data sets and

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:31.590
tables within BigQuery.

00:16:31.590 --> 00:16:35.150
So now that our data is in
BigQuery, and you understand

00:16:35.150 --> 00:16:37.930
the structure of that data,
we're going to talk just a

00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:39.170
little bit about how--

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:41.900
this is probably one of the
simplest things you can do, in

00:16:41.900 --> 00:16:45.270
fact, once your data is in
BigQuery, and that is to

00:16:45.270 --> 00:16:49.950
integrate that data
with spreadsheets.

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:53.050
So, to build, essentially,
reports of various shapes and

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:55.350
sizes using Apps Script.

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:58.650
This is incredibly easy to do.

00:16:58.650 --> 00:17:03.180
So using some of those
aggregated tables, on our

00:17:03.180 --> 00:17:05.319
teams, we build up dashboards.

00:17:05.319 --> 00:17:08.960
So we build relatively
complicated workbooks that

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:11.640
everybody on the team
has access to.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:15.560
We look at a lot of
different metrics.

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:17.420
We slice them in
different ways.

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:19.819
But probably the simplest
would be a simple daily

00:17:19.819 --> 00:17:24.640
dashboard, and these really just
help to highlight high

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:26.270
level KPI trends.

00:17:26.270 --> 00:17:30.770
And they often give you a bit
of a hint that just says,

00:17:30.770 --> 00:17:32.150
maybe we want to go
and look at this.

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:33.940
Retention looks like it's a
little bit off for these

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:36.010
players, or something's
happened, and

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:37.270
our active user base--

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:40.050
the retention dropped over the
next week, and we want to

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:43.030
figure out why.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:44.340
And other people may want
to look at things

00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:45.170
like conversion rates.

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:47.320
So when we have brand new
installs coming in on a given

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:50.430
day or given week, we really
want to monitor the health of

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:53.400
those users, compare them to
other install days, other

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:56.520
install weeks, so that we feel
comfortable continuing with

00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:57.770
our acquisition spend.

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:03.250
So now what I'll do is I'll just
show you very quickly for

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:05.550
the developers that are in the
room, of which I would imagine

00:18:05.550 --> 00:18:11.980
there are lots of you, I'll just
show you how easy it is

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:14.900
to basically integrate BigQuery
with spreadsheets,

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:16.780
and to build reports this way.

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:19.670
So what I've done here is
I've just given you--

00:18:19.670 --> 00:18:22.050
within our games, we tend to
have lots of different types

00:18:22.050 --> 00:18:23.170
of funnels.

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:27.630
So funnels, really, are just
sequential events, and the

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:30.600
fact that we've got all this
raw events data in BigQuery

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:33.520
pretty much means we can define
any funnel we want.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:36.510
And that's pretty significant,
and pretty powerful.

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:40.045
So let's just take this
as an example.

00:18:40.045 --> 00:18:43.420
I've called it the elementary
quest funnel analysis.

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:45.340
But let's say we've got
a product manager.

00:18:45.340 --> 00:18:47.280
This week, they're going to
focus on a very specific part

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:49.390
of the game.

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:51.420
They think they've seen
a bit of drop-off.

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:53.110
They've asked one of the
analysts to go away and do a

00:18:53.110 --> 00:18:54.180
bit of ad hoc analysis.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:57.500
They've identified the issue.

00:18:57.500 --> 00:18:58.990
And now what they
want to see is.

00:18:58.990 --> 00:19:01.140
As they make these iterations
daily, and they keep pushing

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:04.440
these releases, we want to get
that data in front of a

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:05.090
product manager.

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:07.060
And a product manager doesn't
necessarily know how to go

00:19:07.060 --> 00:19:10.360
into BigQuery and write a bunch
of SQL, nor should they

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:13.440
have to, because our analysts
can simply create a new

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:15.860
workbook that's specifically
for that product manager,

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:19.450
define a query that can go away
and look at those tables,

00:19:19.450 --> 00:19:22.570
pull out all the interesting
events that matter, and

00:19:22.570 --> 00:19:27.170
summarize that into a sample
little dashboard.

00:19:27.170 --> 00:19:28.170
So how do you do that?

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:32.100
Well, to be honest, I didn't
even know this stuff existed

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:34.840
about nine months ago until I
did a little bit of digging

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:36.860
around and had a few
chats with Matt.

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:39.610
But we've started using it
heavily, and it's fantastic.

00:19:39.610 --> 00:19:43.070
So you need to go into the
script editor to start working

00:19:43.070 --> 00:19:45.230
with Apps Script, and you'll
find it under the Tools menu.

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:46.890
So if you go to the Tools menu
and you go down here, this

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:48.510
script editor thing-- if you've
ever wondered what that

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:54.090
is, well, for those you that are
new to Apps Script, that

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:55.180
will open the script editor.

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:57.840
And what you'll see here is
essentially JavaScript.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:00.450
So Apps Script is basically
JavaScript.

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:02.420
And I'll just show you.

00:20:02.420 --> 00:20:08.660
So this function here is just
a very simple function which

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:11.900
takes a query, which is just
our SQL statement.

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:17.090
I've put it in a comment down
here, just to illustrate the

00:20:17.090 --> 00:20:18.100
complexity of the query.

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:19.460
So this is a big
complex query.

00:20:19.460 --> 00:20:26.230
It's going query about 200
million rows of data, and it's

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:27.970
going to pull the results back,
and it's going to put

00:20:27.970 --> 00:20:30.510
that into our spreadsheet.

00:20:30.510 --> 00:20:34.490
So how do you connect to
BigQuery within Apps Script?

00:20:34.490 --> 00:20:35.630
Well, it's actually
really simple.

00:20:35.630 --> 00:20:38.270
So here's a little convenience
function that I wrote, which

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:41.370
is run query async, and it's
really just broken down into

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:41.940
three parts.

00:20:41.940 --> 00:20:45.870
So you've got this job
description here, which is

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:46.820
very, very simple to set up.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:49.550
And you can see that we're
passing in our SQL statements.

00:20:49.550 --> 00:20:52.670
That's just a string that
represents our SQL statement.

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:54.920
You can then insert the job.

00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:56.160
So again, very, very simple.

00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:58.460
That's basically passing it off
to BigQuery and asking it

00:20:58.460 --> 00:21:00.420
to actually execute the query.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:03.580
And then all we do here
is we just wait.

00:21:03.580 --> 00:21:05.690
We wait asynchronously,
and we pull to see

00:21:05.690 --> 00:21:07.250
if the job is complete.

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:09.270
And then finally, when the
results come back, we go ahead

00:21:09.270 --> 00:21:14.380
and fetch them just here,
and then we return them.

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:16.620
And that's essentially it.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:21.230
So if we run that now,
hopefully this will--

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:21.640
oh, sorry.

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:23.680
This is one other thing you can
do, which is, again, for

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:26.760
convenience, is you can very
easily just add your own

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:27.440
custom menus.

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:29.200
So you can see this little
bit of code here.

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:29.980
That's all that does.

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:33.030
So I get a nice little menu
item here, and this button

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:35.540
here is hooked to my function.

00:21:35.540 --> 00:21:39.930
Now, the other thing I'll
mention as well--

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:42.350
when you're building up, say,
daily dashboards or monthly

00:21:42.350 --> 00:21:46.340
dashboards, a really nice,
simple way to get them to

00:21:46.340 --> 00:21:48.730
automatically run every day
is with the triggers

00:21:48.730 --> 00:21:49.360
functionality.

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:53.030
So this little icon here
is the triggers.

00:21:53.030 --> 00:21:57.640
To set up a new periodic trigger
is extremely simple.

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:01.760
Just go here and add a trigger,
select the function

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:05.280
that you want to run, select
that you want it to be time

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:07.450
driven, and there's a bunch
of different options here.

00:22:07.450 --> 00:22:10.410
So if this was a daily thing
that we wanted to refresh, I

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:13.150
would select daily, select the
time we want it to run-- so

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:14.950
let's say we want it
to run at 6:00 AM.

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:16.685
We'd save that.

00:22:16.685 --> 00:22:19.080
And now this spreadsheet's going
to automatically run

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:22.360
that query for you at between
6:00 and 7:00 AM.

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:24.320
And so when you get it in the
morning, just pop open your

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:27.400
workbook or open your phone, and
that funnel announcement

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:28.870
is right there for
you to look at.

00:22:28.870 --> 00:22:32.300
So let's just run the
query very quickly.

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:34.870
Again, so this isn't a massive,
massive data set, but

00:22:34.870 --> 00:22:36.170
it's pretty big.

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:38.270
And obviously, we're running
this for our other games as

00:22:38.270 --> 00:22:39.955
well on much larger data sets.

00:22:39.955 --> 00:22:41.900
This is about 200
million rows.

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:44.470
So it's running, and
there we go.

