So all of our interesting data
that we were interested in

00:22:47.770 --> 00:22:50.400
about these different events
throughout our funnel, we've

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:53.160
tracked that, we split it by
Tier 1 countries and non-Tier

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:54.540
1, which is basically
English speaking

00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:56.990
and not English speaking.

00:22:56.990 --> 00:22:59.830
And we can see the results
visualized on our graph below.

00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:03.560
So that's how easy it is,
really, to take these massive

00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:07.330
data sets and actually produce a
workbook, a spreadsheet that

00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:11.650
everybody knows how to access,
and really get this important

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:13.390
data in front of the teams
that are working on

00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:14.640
the games every day.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:24.890
Great.

00:23:24.890 --> 00:23:27.240
So we're going to switch
gears a little bit now.

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:29.440
Again, that was a relatively
simple example of what you can

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:33.260
do to hook BigQuery up to

00:23:33.260 --> 00:23:35.040
spreadsheets using Apps Script.

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:36.640
There's a lot of other things
you can do with Apps Script as

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:38.870
well, so definitely
have a look at it.

00:23:38.870 --> 00:23:41.340
You can convert those
spreadsheets to PDFs, you can

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:42.390
email them to everybody.

00:23:42.390 --> 00:23:44.610
There's loads and loads you
can do with them, so

00:23:44.610 --> 00:23:47.150
definitely have a good
look at that.

