automate optimizations that we

00:24:18.340 --> 00:24:22.050
see or automate tooling
that can help us.

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:24.100
And so the first one we're going
to talk about is a tool

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:26.830
that is called Mailman.

00:24:26.830 --> 00:24:29.650
It's an engagement tool, and
it's built with App Engine.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:35.550
So App Engine--

00:24:35.550 --> 00:24:36.700
we get asked this
a lot as well.

00:24:36.700 --> 00:24:38.550
Why do we use App Engine?

00:24:38.550 --> 00:24:41.130
If anybody wants to go for a
beer later, I can talk to for

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:43.430
about two hours on all the
reasons why I love App Engine.

00:24:43.430 --> 00:24:48.450
App Engine is fantastic, and
integrating it with other

00:24:48.450 --> 00:24:51.680
Google services really
make it even better.

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:54.340
But just simply, if we had to
boil it down into a couple of

00:24:54.340 --> 00:24:57.380
points, it's super productive,
right?

00:24:57.380 --> 00:25:01.430
So I think I've said this
already today, but we just

00:25:01.430 --> 00:25:04.690
like to focus on the problems
and leave some of the heavy

00:25:04.690 --> 00:25:07.270
lifting to the Google
Cloud Platform.

00:25:07.270 --> 00:25:09.700
And it's pretty powerful,
particularly for small teams

00:25:09.700 --> 00:25:11.050
that are trying to grow
their businesses.

00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:13.670
You need every minute of every
day on your products, not on

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:15.710
infrastructure.

00:25:15.710 --> 00:25:17.150
The deployment model's
really cool.

00:25:17.150 --> 00:25:18.630
All of our guys love the
deployment model.

00:25:18.630 --> 00:25:22.450
We can't actually take advantage
of it as much as,

00:25:22.450 --> 00:25:24.740
say, if you had a website that
you could, but we still make

00:25:24.740 --> 00:25:26.370
very, very good use of it.

00:25:26.370 --> 00:25:27.460
And then, of course, scale.

00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:29.105
We mentioned this
once or twice.

00:25:29.105 --> 00:25:30.840
We're going to mention
it again.

00:25:30.840 --> 00:25:33.530
We cannot integrate with any
service that we don't believe

00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:35.400
can scale along with us, because
we're always planning

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:35.970
for success.

00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:39.200
We're expecting big numbers, big
traffic, big concurrency.

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:41.060
And if we're going to build
tools that run alongside our

00:25:41.060 --> 00:25:42.430
games that our games platform's
going to be

00:25:42.430 --> 00:25:45.720
speaking to at that sort of
level, we have to make the

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:46.350
right decisions.

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:47.470
And we feel very, very
good about our

00:25:47.470 --> 00:25:48.670
choice of App Engine.

00:25:48.670 --> 00:25:52.600
We've been working with it
for about two years now.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:54.430
So Mailman, just to dig into--

00:25:54.430 --> 00:25:55.700
this is just one of the
tools we've built.

00:25:55.700 --> 00:25:56.370
We've built a number.

00:25:56.370 --> 00:25:59.020
We decided to focus on
these two today.

00:25:59.020 --> 00:26:04.600
So Mailman really is an
automated delivery mechanism

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:07.290
or delivery tool
for messaging.

00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:09.500
It's really important
within our games.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:10.850
People aren't playing
our games all

00:26:10.850 --> 00:26:12.510
day, and that's healthy.

00:26:12.510 --> 00:26:17.070
Some of them actually do, which
we're worried about, but

00:26:17.070 --> 00:26:18.050
most of them don't, right?

00:26:18.050 --> 00:26:20.130
Most of them are normal people,
and they come and go,

00:26:20.130 --> 00:26:22.790
and they play a lot of
different games.

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:27.960
And so when we do our ad hoc
analysis, and we see the sorts

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:30.620
of drop-off points that maybe
are concerning to us, and we

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:33.620
see where people get stuck
within the game, sometimes

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:34.900
it's too late for us.

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:37.410
And because they got stuck in
the game at a certain point

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:40.580
that we've now identified,
they're not

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:42.320
planning on coming back.

00:26:42.320 --> 00:26:44.350
And so this is when we have to
basically reach out to them.

00:26:44.350 --> 00:26:45.790
And this is just one
case, right?

00:26:45.790 --> 00:26:49.230
We reach out to our players all
the time through email,

00:26:49.230 --> 00:26:53.020
through push notifications and
Facebook notifications.

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:58.200
So the logical components
of Mailman are lists.

00:26:58.200 --> 00:26:59.890
Lists really answer the who.

00:26:59.890 --> 00:27:04.550
So the powerful bit about
lists is that lists are

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:06.640
basically groups of message
recipients, so

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:08.870
they represent players.

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:11.440
And the list can be defined
with a query.

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:13.360
So anything we can write a query
for, anything that we

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:15.780
turn up in our ad hoc analysis,
we can just define a

00:27:15.780 --> 00:27:18.420
new list with a query.

00:27:18.420 --> 00:27:20.840
We use a little bit of
templating to make sure that

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:23.910
we can use those same queries
over and over daily, if they

00:27:23.910 --> 00:27:25.330
need to be refreshed
daily, but it's a

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.370
pretty powerful thing.

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:30.730
And what actually happens
technically under the hood

00:27:30.730 --> 00:27:36.280
when one of those lists are
created is that under the

00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:38.760
hood, we basically make
a query to BigQuery.

00:27:38.760 --> 00:27:40.890
And for those of you that are
familiar with App Engine, we

00:27:40.890 --> 00:27:44.085
store the results, no matter how
large they are-- we store

00:27:44.085 --> 00:27:46.800
those results in
the Blobstore.

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:49.400
And so jobs, when they
actually run--

00:27:49.400 --> 00:27:50.700
the messaging jobs--

00:27:50.700 --> 00:27:54.930
this is really where we take
advantage of App Engine's

00:27:54.930 --> 00:28:00.030
scale and parallelism, because
we make use of the MapReduce

00:28:00.030 --> 00:28:03.700
API and the pipeline APIs, and
that means that essentially,

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:06.210
we can spin up a lot of
instances to go away and map

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:08.420
over the results that we got
back from our query.

00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:10.100
And so jobs really represent--

00:28:10.100 --> 00:28:15.230
if lists are the who, then jobs
really answer the what,

00:28:15.230 --> 00:28:18.500
the when, and the where, because
what happens when this

00:28:18.500 --> 00:28:20.940
MapReduce job runs across all
these instances that just sort

00:28:20.940 --> 00:28:23.960
of fire up magically is that for
every single recipient and

00:28:23.960 --> 00:28:26.570
message that we're going to
send, we enqueue a task.

00:28:26.570 --> 00:28:29.840
And so sometimes we run huge,
huge volumes of messaging,

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.180
whether it's email, push
notifications, Facebook

00:28:32.180 --> 00:28:33.370
notifications.

00:28:33.370 --> 00:28:35.160
You could very easily run a job
one night that's going to

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:37.570
be to millions of users.

00:28:37.570 --> 00:28:40.940
And App Engine can handle
that pretty seamlessly.

00:28:40.940 --> 00:28:43.670
And one of the things you'll
find when you start working

00:28:43.670 --> 00:28:45.670
with App Engine is that there's
so many great APIs and

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:48.600
services that are made available
to you when you

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:50.570
build on that platform.

00:28:50.570 --> 00:28:52.310
And so one of the ways in which
we-- there's a feature

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:54.760
called ETA, and ETA essentially
means that you can

00:28:54.760 --> 00:28:56.460
specify the earliest time
that you want a

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:57.970
specific task to run.

00:28:57.970 --> 00:29:00.460
And so we actually use the ETA
feature within the task use to

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:05.110
make sure that part of our query
on that list, one of the

00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:06.870
columns of data that comes
back for every row

00:29:06.870 --> 00:29:08.610
is actually a hint.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:11.890
And it hints to us what time of
day we should actually send

00:29:11.890 --> 00:29:14.570
out a message to make sure that
we get the highest chance

00:29:14.570 --> 00:29:16.920
that a user's going to respond
to that and engage with that

00:29:16.920 --> 00:29:18.400
message and come back
to the game.

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:20.290
And so we use a lot.

00:29:20.290 --> 00:29:24.985
And obviously, we deliver across
the different channels.

00:29:24.985 --> 00:29:27.590
So that's Mailman.

00:29:27.590 --> 00:29:28.700
The next one we're going to talk
to you about-- this is

00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:30.960
the last one--

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:36.750
is called Cobra, and Cobra is
also built on App Engine.

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:40.220
So Cobra's really interesting
because as you can imagine,

00:29:40.220 --> 00:29:40.900
once your game's mature--

00:29:40.900 --> 00:29:43.000
you launch a game, it's out
there for three or six months.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:44.590
You're doing loads
of optimizations.

00:29:44.590 --> 00:29:45.760
You really start to push it.

00:29:45.760 --> 00:29:47.960
It's getting bigger and
bigger and bigger.

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:50.520
And slowly, what you see
happening is that you can't

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:53.600
just address users that
are, say, right on

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:54.610
the bleeding edge.

00:29:54.610 --> 00:29:56.990
And you can't really just
address users that are on day

00:29:56.990 --> 00:29:58.310
one or day two or day three.

00:29:58.310 --> 00:30:00.810
But there's lots of different
strategies that you want to

00:30:00.810 --> 00:30:05.240
deploy to make sure that you
have the best chance at

00:30:05.240 --> 00:30:08.230
monetizing users at all of
the different stages

00:30:08.230 --> 00:30:09.610
of their life cycle.

00:30:09.610 --> 00:30:11.100
And so that's what Cobra
does for us.

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:14.660
Cobra is basically a pricing and
promotions engine which is

00:30:14.660 --> 00:30:15.910
aware of players' profiles.

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:21.370
Cobra is loosely integrated
with BigQuery, but is also

00:30:21.370 --> 00:30:24.370
heavily integrated with
our games platform.

00:30:24.370 --> 00:30:27.280
And the other thing that it does
is it acts as a middleman

00:30:27.280 --> 00:30:28.830
through all the transactions.

00:30:28.830 --> 00:30:31.800
No matter what the platform,
all of our transactions

00:30:31.800 --> 00:30:36.240
securely flow through Mailman,
are authenticated and

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:39.350
validated, and then
they proceed.

00:30:39.350 --> 00:30:42.000
So if we think about the pricing
and promotions engine,

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.380
what's actually happening today
is a very iterative

00:30:44.380 --> 00:30:46.340
process where we go away and
we do a lot of ad hoc

00:30:46.340 --> 00:30:51.530
analysis, and from that ad hoc
analysis, we come up with

00:30:51.530 --> 00:30:52.130
strategies.

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:55.100
So different pricing and
promotion strategies that we

00:30:55.100 --> 00:31:00.330
want to basically program into
Cobra, and then deploy.

00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:03.620
And when someone actually does
interact with one of these

00:31:03.620 --> 00:31:06.960
offers, or a promotion, or a
response to maybe a subtle

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:09.720
change in some of the pricing,
we record that.

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:12.570
So they make a purchase, it's
tagged with a bunch of

00:31:12.570 --> 00:31:14.580
information about the
configuration that they

00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:18.480
responded to, and that flows
down into our games platform,

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:21.660
which, again, nightly, comes
back up into BigQuery.

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:24.510
And so we do a lot of manual
iterative processes there.

00:31:24.510 --> 00:31:26.980
And that works really,
really well.

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:29.590
But one of the next things that
we're looking at is how

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:31.370
we can use something called the
Prediction API, and this

00:31:31.370 --> 00:31:34.760
is another from Google which
I'm told is really, really

00:31:34.760 --> 00:31:38.820
heavily used internally, and not
used that much externally.

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:41.210
But we definitely have
a use case for it.

00:31:41.210 --> 00:31:43.500
So just at a super high level,
because we're running out of

00:31:43.500 --> 00:31:51.020
time, the Prediction API kind
of has two functions.

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:52.490
If you have a model--

00:31:52.490 --> 00:31:54.660
so you've got a lot of raw data,
which obviously we do,

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:58.070
and many of you, I would
imagine, have as well--

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:03.040
and you think that if you did
some analysis on that data,

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:05.710
you might be able to come up
with some statistically

00:32:05.710 --> 00:32:10.700
significant indicators
of an outcome.

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:14.340
So for us, within Cobra, that
might be, this user's profile

00:32:14.340 --> 00:32:17.930
looks like this right now.

00:32:17.930 --> 00:32:21.910
Which type of offer do I think
they're most likely to convert

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:25.250
with, or to convert on?

00:32:25.250 --> 00:32:27.010
So basically, you just put
a bunch of data in cloud

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:30.380
storage, you point that at
the training endpoint.

00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:32.260
Prediction will suck up all
the data, will train

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:33.140
the model for you.

00:32:33.140 --> 00:32:35.700
And when it's complete, you can
actually query that model.

00:32:35.700 --> 00:32:38.830
So you can query that
statistical model with,

00:32:38.830 --> 00:32:41.140
essentially, what would be a
row of data-- so a row of

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:42.120
these features.

00:32:42.120 --> 00:32:43.980
And that would try and
predict what that

00:32:43.980 --> 00:32:47.270
example value might be.

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:49.640
So Cobra with Prediction.

00:32:49.640 --> 00:32:50.910
You can kind of see how
that would work.

00:32:50.910 --> 00:32:53.480
And so the way in which we might
use it, or one of the

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:59.510
ways in which we might use it,
is to just help us train on

00:32:59.510 --> 00:33:03.310
our financial data, train on our
profiles data, and try and

00:33:03.310 --> 00:33:06.110
help us make even better
decisions about what kind of

00:33:06.110 --> 00:33:11.670
offers to surface to players
based on where they are in

00:33:11.670 --> 00:33:13.540
their lifetime.

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:14.720
And that's a pretty
powerful thing.

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:16.500
So that's something we're
experimenting with, and

00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:19.880
hopefully, maybe next year, we
can come back in and talk

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:22.860
about how that went.

00:33:22.860 --> 00:33:28.400
So just to sort of recap, my big
thing is, we've grown the

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:31.620
social team at Gamesys from
about 4 people sitting in a

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:35.550
little hallway to 100 people
that occupy most of a floor.

00:33:35.550 --> 00:33:39.250
And I think one of the ways in
which we've done that is that

00:33:39.250 --> 00:33:43.370
we try and stand on the
shoulders of giants, and not

00:33:43.370 --> 00:33:44.670
try and replicate a
lot of work that

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:46.320
can be done by others.

00:33:46.320 --> 00:33:48.520
And these are fantastic
products.

00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:51.100
And if you invest the time into
understanding how they

00:33:51.100 --> 00:33:54.340
work and what they can do for
you, you'll spend less time on

00:33:54.340 --> 00:33:56.950
all the boring, painful stuff.

00:33:56.950 --> 00:33:59.530
And you'll really be able to get
at your data, build really

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:02.270
cool tools, and focus
on your game,

00:34:02.270 --> 00:34:05.860
which I think is paramount.

